BFAFT_DIS1_EXPLAIN: I didn't
FOLLOW_DIS1_EXPLAIN: I think that when it is something that can change your life, you need to have that confirmed, regardless of the risks of the test. If it is confirmed then the doctors will have the information they need to proceed, and if it is not, a 1% chance of complication is worth the verification that the usually correct mammogram was in fact incorrect.
BFAFT_DIS2_EXPLAIN: I didn't change it, but I do want to note something. If I had a friend who came to me specifically for advice about this and whether or not they should have it done, my response would be tailored to the person. This is not the same to me as a mammogram. Because it has to do with potentially bringing a child into the world, it needs more nuance. If the friend didn't want to have it done, I would recommend they not get it done. If the friend did want it done, then I would recommend they do it. It would very much be dependent on the friend and their actions and thoughts on the matter.
FOLLOW_DIS2_EXPLAIN: Again, this would be incredibly individual. I am not someone who thinks that not being neurotypical is a bad thing. People can have DS and live amazing lives. That said, not every single parent has the capacity to raise a special-needs child. And it is the right of the human who is gestating to choose what to do with their bodily autonomy. Meaning, if they decide that is not for them, then that is their choice. If an amnio would help in that case to make an informed decision, then I would recommend it. If the friend was unconcerned about the possibility of DS, and a diagnosis would not impact the continuation of the pregnancy, then I would recommend against it. There is no blanket statement recommendation on this one.

I work taking care of several people with down syndrome and know the quality of life that these people still enjoy regardless of their condition.

comment: I apologize if any of my answers came off emotional, I lost a very close family friend to breast cancer and my child had a high chance of down syndrome due to my medical condition and medication. I was not supposed to get pregnant with her, but my medication made my birth control fail so I had her. Comparing the two hit very close to home and one is comparing saving life and the other is almost devaluing life. Thank you for letting me participate, I appreciate you letting me share my views.
